A talk by Naushir Patuck from Raspberry Pi in November 2024 mentioned that Raspberry Pi were considering the possibility of a μC with MIPI CSI-2 support.
  (Registration required to access webinar)
  https://www.digikey.com/en/blog/webinar-introduction-raspberry-pi-imaging-and-computer-vision-tools
  Times are from beginning ofthe webinar not Naushir Patuck's part of the webinar:
  18:40 Hailo 8 26 TOPS versus Hailo 8 L 13 TOPS - both of these connect over the PCIe link with the Raspberry PI and because of this they're only compatible with Raspberry Pi 5
  22:10 you can run the very same models on the CPU but instead of 30 FPS you'd be running at 1 or a half FPS - like a 30 times speed up at least in these cases here
  27:00 Raspberry Pi AI Camera - AI HAT can only be used on Rapberry Pi 5 because of PCIe thing - Raspberry Pi AI Camera can be run on any Raspberry PI - IMX500 has AI built-in - up to 2 TOPS - in-line with the sensor frame so very low latency - including the Pi Zeros
  39:40 Q&A begins
  39:44 Will the RPi camera work with Pico? Right now no because we use a standard RPi camera connector - there's no socket on the Pico 2 W that attaches to this interface - we're looking at this to see what we can do 
  45:30 Power consumption? Depends on workload 1 to 1.5 W for AI Camera typically at 30 FPS object recognition network, for AI Hat boards higher closer to 2 to 2.5 W range.
  47:00 Synchronisation? For GS cameras electronic connection. Still working on software synchronisation for V3 cameras - still in beta
  53:00 OpenCV? Indirectly yes - OpenCV does not interface directly with libcamera - opening a camera source in OpenCV is possible but not easy - working with OpenCV team to integrate libcamera directly with their library
  56:50 PCIe? Only one PCIe connector on the board - either the AI HAT or M.2 drive the would occupy that - can buy 3rd party PCIe switch hat for multiple PCIe devices.
  61:05 End.

