Microchip SAMA7G54
  It's a MPU with a CSI-2 interface and is also aimed at low power consumption according to
  https://www.elektormagazine.com/news/first-single-core-mpu-with-mipi-csi-2-camera-interface-and-advanced-audio-features
  "Microchip is committed to maintaining the lowest power MPU portfolio in the market. The SAMA7G54 extends this low-power trend into the 1GHz performance class of Linux®-capable MPUs by providing flexible low-power modes, as well as voltage and frequency scaling."
  Obviously, adoption will be greatly enhanced by the marketing genius at Microchip who wants 350 EUR to shove the thing on a circuit board:
  https://www.microchip.com/en-us/development-tool/EV21H18A
  Microchip do produce a SOM based on it for 70 EUR 
  https://www.microchipdirect.com/dev-tools/EA16Z43A
  Or 3 for 200 USD:
  https://www.microchip.com/en-us/development-tool/ea16z43a
  but:
    "It is not recommended to use industrial automated reflow process with oven to solder the product on the mother board, as the process might impact the System-On-Module reliability.
    Work Around: Solder the System-On-Module on the mother board manually."
    I'm not sure if it can be treated as a competitor given that there's no built-in WiFi (another module has to be added for that) and the soldering problem with the SOM (I'd thought that SOM manufacturers had solved that some time ago - sometimes simply by popping a metal can over most of the SOM).
    With the soldering problem with the SOM the only way to get the thing into a production design would be if Microchip provide good PCB reference design files.
    The SAMA7G54 is over 2 years old now so Microchip may have produced something newer.
  Posted a question on Microchip forums on 23 December 2024
  μC or μP With MIPI CSI-2 Support
