Raspberry Pi 5
  Camera and DSI display connectors are interchangeable, so you can have one of each, or two the same.
  Broadcom BCM2712 quad-core Arm Cortex A76 processor @ 2.4GHz, 
  BUT: No hardware support for low power sleep mode so wake up time is limited to Linux boot time.
  BUT: Hardware video encoding does not appear to be supported:
  https://www.raspberrypi.com/documentation/computers/processors.html#bcm2712
  "4Kp60 HEVC hardware decode"
  "Other CODECs run in software"
  "H264 1080p30 encode (from ISP) ~30–40% CPU"
  https://forums.raspberrypi.com/viewtopic.php?t=378329
  "There is no hardware H264 or H265 encoder on Pi5. The CPUs can do 4k30 in software with libx264 as long as you don't enable too many of the encode bells and whistles. Yes it increases CPU load."
  https://raspberrypi.stackexchange.com/questions/144475/did-the-raspberry-pi-5-drop-hardware-encoding-support
  "The Pi5 has no hardware support for video encoding."
  https://forums.raspberrypi.com/viewtopic.php?p=2139082#p2139126
  "There is no codec hardware acceleration except for HEVC decode."
  https://www.raspberrypi.com/news/introducing-raspberry-pi-5/#comment-1594055
  "Ok, this is a big one… The problem is that video encoding is not a standard. You can put as much or as little effort into encoding as you like, on Pi 1, 2, 3, & 4 the encoding quality (for the bitrate) was relatively poor. The nice thing about using the processors to do this is you get to choose exactly what balance between quality and bitrate you want. Obviously, the bad thing is the power consumption, but actually it only takes around 1 processor to encode 1080p60 with our default settings (which is still better quality than the PI 4 hardware encoder). We think it might be possible with the right settings to be able to hit 4K encode at around 24fps, but we’ve not been optimising in that direction yet.
  In future we’ll have to do something, but for Pi 5 we feel the hardware encode is a mm^2 too far."
  
